        "trailText":"<strong>Editorial:</strong> The Hawaiian lifeguard and fearless surfer died on duty aged 31 and he is now being celebrated in a new documentary",
        "headline":"In praise of ... Eddie Aikau",
        "body":"<p>\"Eddie would go!\" This is the line surfers use to encourage one another to tackle big waves and show some bravado. Eddie Aikau was an Hawaiian lifeguard and fearless surfer who died on duty in 1978 aged 31, and whose achievements are celebrated in <a href=\"http://xgames.espn.go.com/surfing/article/9749881/legend-eddie-aikau-premieres-espn-films-30-30\" title=\"\">a new documentary</a>, Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau. In 10 years, he made more than 500 rescues in Waimea Bay. No lives were lost under his watch, though he often had to brave monstrous 9ft waves. A dedicated peacemaker, he also worked tirelessly to break up fights between the Australian and US surfing teams. In the 1980s, shortly after his death, the sport morphed into a heavily branded multimillion-dollar industry: all logos and big money. But stripped from those artifices, surfing remains much more than just an athletic endeavour: it's a practice that teaches you to be respectful of the environment, courageous in the face of danger, and compassionate towards others.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419201222|2013-10-07T10:21:29Z|95384003b60e09246a085b7ad9e2ef2a9d6f7920 -->",
