      "id":"commentisfree/2013/oct/06/nhs-england-patients-experts",
      "sectionId":"commentisfree",
      "sectionName":"Comment is free",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-06T18:29:00Z",
      "webTitle":"NHS England is finally taking expert advice – from the patients | Jackie Ashley",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/06/nhs-england-patients-experts",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/06/nhs-england-patients-experts",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"26",
        "trailText":"<p><strong>Jackie Ashley:</strong> A people's panel to hear patients' views is forcing doctors to re-evaluate their approach to medicine</p>",
        "headline":"NHS England is finally taking expert advice – from the patients",
        "body":"<p>Why don't we listen to Jonathan? We listen to politicians, doctors, nurses' trade union leaders, commentators and academics … but we don't listen to Jonathan. Jonathan is the ultimate health expert. He has had kidney failure for 30 years, has spent 14 years on dialysis and is currently on his fourth kidney transplant. If you want to know about managing kidney conditions, he's your man. Yet it has taken 30 years for someone to ask him what his views are.</p><p>Look away now because – shock, horror – this is a good news story. At last he and people like him have been advising the country's top health professionals and administrators on how to shape the health service of the future.</p><p>Jonathan, and 13 other people with a long-term medical conditions, ranging from permanent paralysis through incurable bowel disease to severe heart problems, have been  part of a \"people's panel\", attending a two-day conference last week on the way the NHS needs to change.</p><p>There have been, of course, endless conferencesut in the past one thing has been missing: the patients. Yet now for Dr Martin McShane, the director of long-term conditions for NHS England, patients' voices are needed for what he calls the \"radically new approach\" in the NHS. <a href=\"http://www.futureofhealth.co.uk/\" title=\"\">The Future of Health</a>, organised by NHS England along with UCL Partners and the political information company Dods, brought together more than a thousand experts to hear the views of the \"people's panel\".</p><p>The need for change is obvious. According to McShane, 70% of current health spending goes on the 15 million people in England who suffer from one or more long-term conditions. The twin challenges of people living longer and with unhealthier lifestyles (smoking, alcohol, obesity) means that number is set to increase dramatically. It's called modern life.</p><p>For many of those with a long-term condition, it is not about \"getting better\". That won't happen. It's about managing the condition as well as possible, with the right support, the right medication and the right medical conversation.  And according to the \"people's panel\", that's rare.</p><p>Listen to Anya, who had to drop out of Cambridge where she was studying medicine when she developed a neurological condition: \"There's too much talk about clinical pathways, what we need are real pathways.\" Anya strongly supports self-management of long-term diseases, but this is only possible where the patients' needs are seen as more than just a clinical issue.</p><p>That means bringing the Cinderellas of the healthcare system – mental health and social care – much higher up the agenda. Dementia is all around us – you could almost call it the new cancer. Depression, unsurprisingly, follows incurable illness like a faithful dog. Help around the house, to perform the most basic tasks, can make the difference between someone really living and someone merely being kept alive.</p><p>Patients spot the simple things that can make a difference, such as a new ward for people undergoing the transition to rehabilitation; better curtains for privacy; less absurd form-filling (is it necessary to ask a 63-year-old whether she's on the contraceptive pill?).</p><p>During the course of the conference, NHS professionals had many Homer Simpson \"doh\" moments. One professor admitted he finally understood that self-management was about the patient trying to regain control, and that quality of life was the important thing. Doctors were asked to commit to spending five minutes a day talking to \"a person\" rather than seeing people as just \"patients\". Co-production is the new watchword, getting patients at every level to design services.</p><p>McShane's \"doh\" moment was realising that it's not just what goes on in hospital that is important. That's the sexy part, the bit that hospital dramas focus on. \"I was a surgeon for nine years, heroically striding around in green scrubs,\" he says, \"but all of that is futile if it's not followed up when the patient leaves hospital.\" That's just one of the challenges he has promised to report back to the people's panel on in six months' time.</p><p>All credit must go to NHS England for its bravery in staging such an event. It is the first time I have heard the most senior health professionals in the country being blasted by patients, rather than lecturing to attentive audiences. But there is still a long way to go.</p><p>Unhappily, the patients were not involved in planning the conference, so long distances had to be walked, an over-full programme left no time for rest and many of those involved had to spend a couple of days recovering.</p><p>This is real news. The pathetic point-scoring spat between health secretary Jeremy Hunt and his opposite number, Andy Burnham, over a past hospital scandal is dominating the headlines. But the health challenges this country faces are huge, complex, intractable; and away from the barneys and bluster, good work is being done. Jonathan and his friends are being heard.</p><p><a href=\"http://twitter.com/JackieAshley\" title=\"\"><em>Twitter: @JackieAshley</em></a><em> </em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419188273|2013-10-07T10:21:29Z|2d874444e9118da26f5288bbd38377aa6b9c59fc -->",
